# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: core-plug
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:core-plug/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:core-plug/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:core-plug/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:core-plug/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:core-plug/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:core-plug/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:core-plug/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:core-plug/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:core-plug/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:core-plug/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:core-plug/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:core-plug/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:core-plug/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:core-plug/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:core-plug/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:core-plug/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:core-plug/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:core-plug/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:core-plug/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:core-plug/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:core-plug/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:core-plug/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska is the largest U.S. state by area—comprising more total area than the next three largest states of Texas, California, and Montana combined—and is the world's largest semi-exclave and seventh-largest subnational division.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] With a population of 740,133 in 2024, it is the third-least populous and most sparsely populated state in the U.S., but the most populous territory in North America located mostly north of the 60th parallel, with more than quadruple the combined populations of Northern Canada and Greenland.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska contains the four largest cities in the United States by area, including the state capital, Juneau.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska's most populous city is Anchorage, and approximately half the state's residents live within its metropolitan area.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Indigenous people have lived in Alaska for thousands of years, and it is widely believed that the region served as the entry point for the initial settlement of the Americas by way of the Bering land bridge.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Russian Empire was the first to actively colonize the area beginning in the 18th century, eventually establishing Russian America, which spanned most of the current state and promoted and maintained a native Alaskan Creole population.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The expense and logistical difficulty of maintaining this distant possession prompted its sale to the U.S. in 1867 for US$7.2 million, equivalent to $166 million in 2025.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The area went through several administrative changes before becoming organized as a territory on May 11, 1912.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] It was admitted as the 49th state of the U.S. on January 3, 1959.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] An abundance of natural resources—including commercial fishing and the extraction of natural gas and oil—has enabled Alaska to have one of the highest per capita incomes in the United States, despite having one of the smallest economies.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Armed Forces bases and tourism also contribute to the economy; more than half of Alaska is federally owned, containing national forests, national parks, and wildlife refuges.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] It is among the most irreligious states and one of the first to legalize recreational marijuana.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska has the highest proportion of Native Americans of any U.S. state, at 22 percent.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The name *Alaska* (Russian: Аля́ска, romanized: *Aljáska*) was introduced during the Russian colonial period when it was used to refer to the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] It was derived from an Aleut-language idiom, *alaxsxaq*, meaning 'the mainland' or, more literally, 'the object towards which the action of the sea is directed'.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Numerous Indigenous peoples occupied Alaska for thousands of years before the arrival of European peoples to the area.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Linguistic and DNA studies done here have provided evidence for the settlement of North America by way of the Bering land bridge.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] At the Upward Sun River site in the Tanana Valley in Alaska, remains of a six-week-old infant were found.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The baby's DNA showed that she belonged to a population that was genetically separate from other Native groups present elsewhere in the New World at the end of the Pleistocene.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Ben Potter, the University of Alaska Fairbanks archaeologist who unearthed the remains at the Upward Sun River site in 2013, named this new group Ancient Beringian.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Tlingit people developed a society with a matrilineal kinship system of property inheritance and descent in what is present Southeast Alaska, along with parts of British Columbia and the Yukon.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Also in the Southeast were the Haida, now well known for their unique arts.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Tsimshian people came to Alaska from British Columbia in 1887, when President Grover Cleveland, and later the U.S.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Congress, granted them permission to settle on Annette Island and found the town of Metlakatla, Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] All three of these peoples, as well as other Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest Coast, experienced smallpox outbreaks from the late 18th through the mid-19th century, with the most devastating epidemics occurring in the 1830s and 1860s, resulting in high fatalities and social disruption.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Some researchers believe the first Russian settlement in Alaska was established in the 17th century.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] According to this hypothesis, in 1648 several koches of Semyon Dezhnyov's expedition came ashore in Alaska by storm and founded this settlement.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] This hypothesis is based on the testimony of Chukchi geographer Nikolai Daurkin, who had visited Alaska in 1764–1765 and who had reported on a village on the Kheuveren River, populated by "bearded men" who "pray to the icons".
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Some modern researchers associate the Kheuveren with the Koyuk River.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The first European vessel to reach Alaska is generally held to be the *St.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Gabriel* under the authority of the surveyor M.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Fyodorov on August 21, 1732, during an expedition of Siberian Cossack A.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Shestakov and Russian explorer Dmitry Pavlutsky (1729–1735).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Another European contact with Alaska occurred in 1741, when Vitus Bering led an expedition for the Russian Navy aboard the *St.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] After his crew returned to Russia with sea otter pelts judged to be the finest fur in the world, small associations of fur traders began to sail from the shores of Siberia toward the Aleutian Islands.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The first permanent European settlement was founded in 1784.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] From 1774 to 1800, Spain sent several expeditions to Alaska to assert its claim over the Pacific Northwest, which it considered part of New Spain, administered from Mexico City, Mexico.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 1789, a Spanish settlement and fort were built in Nootka Sound.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] These expeditions gave names to places such as Valdez, Bucareli Sound, and Cordova.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Later, the Russian-American Company carried out an expanded colonization program during the early-to-mid-19th century.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Sitka, renamed New Archangel from 1804 to 1867, on Baranof Island in the Alexander Archipelago in what is now Southeast Alaska, became the capital of Russian America.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] It remained the capital after the colony was transferred to the United States.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Russians never fully colonized Alaska, and the colony was never very profitable.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Evidence of Russian settlement in names and churches survives throughout southeastern Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Seward, the United States Secretary of State under President Andrew Johnson, negotiated the Alaska Purchase, referred to pejoratively as Seward's Folly, with the Russians for $7.2 million.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Russian emperor Alexander II also planned the sale.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The purchase was made on March 30, 1867.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Six months later the commissioners arrived in Sitka and the formal transfer was arranged.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The flag-raising took place at Fort Sitka on October 18, 1867.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In the ceremony, 250 uniformed U.S. soldiers marched to the governor's house at "Castle Hill", where the Russian troops lowered the Russian flag and the U.S. flag was raised.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] This event is celebrated as Alaska Day, a legal holiday on October 18.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska was loosely governed by the military initially and was administered as a district starting in 1884, with a governor appointed by the United States president.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] A federal district court was headquartered in Sitka.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] For most of Alaska's first decade under the United States flag, Sitka was the only community inhabited by American settlers.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] They organized "a provisional city government", which was Alaska's first municipal government, but not in a legal sense.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Legislation allowing Alaskan communities to legally incorporate as cities arrived in 1900, and home rule for cities was extremely limited or unavailable until statehood took effect in 1959.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Starting in the 1890s and stretching in some places to the early 1910s, gold rushes in Alaska and the nearby Yukon Territory brought thousands of miners and settlers to Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 1912, Alaska was incorporated as an organized territory.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska's capital, which had been in Sitka until 1906, was moved north to Juneau.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Construction of the Alaska Governor's Mansion began that same year.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] European immigrants from Norway and Sweden also settled in southeast Alaska, where they entered the fishing and logging industries.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] During World War II, the Aleutian Islands Campaign focused on Attu, Agattu and Kiska, all of which were occupied by the Empire of Japan.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] During the Japanese occupation, an American civilian and two United States Navy personnel were killed at Attu and Kiska respectively, and almost 50 Aleut civilians and eight sailors were interned in Japan.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] About half of the Aleuts died during the period of internment.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Unalaska/Dutch Harbor and Adak became significant bases for the United States Army, United States Army Air Forces and United States Navy.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The United States Lend-Lease program involved flying American warplanes through Canada to Fairbanks and then Nome.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Soviet pilots took possession of these aircraft, ferrying them to fight the German invasion of the Soviet Union.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The construction of military bases contributed to the population growth of some Alaskan cities.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Statehood for Alaska was an important cause of James Wickersham early in his tenure as a congressional delegate.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Decades later, the statehood movement gained its first real momentum following a territorial referendum in 1946.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Alaska Statehood Committee and Alaska's Constitutional Convention soon followed.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Statehood supporters also found themselves fighting major battles against political foes, mostly in the U.S.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska was officially proclaimed a state on January 3, 1959.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] On March 27, 1964, the Good Friday earthquake killed 133 people and destroyed several villages and portions of large coastal communities, mainly by the resultant tsunamis and landslides.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] It was the fourth-most-powerful earthquake in recorded history, with a moment magnitude of 9.2, more than a thousand times as powerful as the 1989 San Francisco earthquake.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The time of day (5:36 pm), time of year (spring) and location of the epicenter were all cited as factors in potentially sparing thousands of lives, particularly in Anchorage.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Good Friday earthquake lasted 4 minutes and 38 seconds.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Six hundred miles (970 km) of fault ruptured at once and moved up to 60 ft (18 m), releasing about 500 years of stress buildup.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Soil liquefaction, fissures, landslides, and other ground failures caused major structural damage in several communities and much damage to property.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Anchorage sustained great destruction or damage to many inadequately earthquake-engineered houses, buildings, and infrastructure (paved streets, sidewalks, water and sewer mains, electrical systems, and other human-made equipment), particularly in the several landslide zones along Knik Arm.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Two hundred miles (320 km) southwest, some areas near Kodiak were permanently raised by 30 feet (9 m).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Southeast of Anchorage, areas around the head of Turnagain Arm near Girdwood and Portage dropped as much as 8 feet (2.4 m), requiring reconstruction and fill to raise the Seward Highway above the new high tide mark.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In Prince William Sound, Port Valdez suffered a massive underwater landslide, resulting in the deaths of 32 people between the collapse of the Valdez city harbor and docks, and inside the ship that was docked there at the time.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Nearby, a 27-foot (8.2 m) tsunami destroyed the village of Chenega, killing 23 of the 68 people who lived there; survivors out-ran the wave, climbing to high ground.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Post-quake tsunamis severely affected Whittier, Seward, Kodiak, and other Alaskan communities, as well as people and property in British Columbia, Washington, Oregon, and California.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Tsunamis also caused damage in Hawaii and Japan.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Evidence of motion directly related to the earthquake was also reported from Florida and Texas.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska had never experienced a major disaster in a highly populated area before and had very limited resources for dealing with the effects of such an event.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In Anchorage, at the urging of geologist Lidia Selkregg, the City of Anchorage and the Alaska State Housing Authority appointed a team of 40 scientists, including geologists, soil scientists, and engineers, to assess the damage done by the earthquake to the city.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The team, called the Engineering and Geological Evaluation Group, was headed by Ruth A.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Schmidt, a geology professor at the University of Alaska Anchorage.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The team of scientists came into conflict with local developers and downtown business owners who wanted to immediately rebuild; the scientists wanted to identify future dangers to ensure that the rebuilt infrastructure would be safe.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The team produced a report on May 8, 1964, just a little more than a month after the earthquake.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The United States military, which has a large active presence in Alaska, also stepped in to assist within moments of the end of the quake.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Army rapidly re-established communications with the lower 48 states, deployed troops to assist the citizens of Anchorage, and dispatched a convoy to Valdez.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] On the advice of military and civilian leaders, President Lyndon B.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Johnson declared all of Alaska a major disaster area the day after the quake.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Coast Guard deployed ships to isolated coastal communities to assist with immediate needs.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Bad weather and poor visibility hampered air rescue and observation efforts the day after the quake, but on Sunday the 29th the situation improved and rescue helicopters and observation aircraft were deployed.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] A military airlift immediately began shipping relief supplies to Alaska, eventually delivering 2,570,000 pounds (1,170,000 kg) of food and other supplies.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Broadcast journalist, Genie Chance, assisted in recovery and relief efforts, staying on the KENI air waves over Anchorage for more than 24 continuous hours as the voice of calm from her temporary post within the Anchorage Public Safety Building.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] She was effectively designated as the public safety officer by the city's police chief.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Army Corps of Engineers led the effort to rebuild roads, clear debris, and establish new townsites for communities that had been completely destroyed, at a cost of $110 million.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The West Coast and Alaska Tsunami Warning Center was formed as a direct response to the disaster.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Federal disaster relief funds paid for reconstruction as well as financially supporting the devastated infrastructure of Alaska's government, spending hundreds of millions of dollars that helped keep Alaska financially solvent until the discovery of massive oil deposits at Prudhoe Bay.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Defense Department, the Alaska National Guard founded the Alaska Division of Emergency Services to respond to any future disasters.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The 1968 discovery of oil at Prudhoe Bay and the 1977 completion of the Trans-Alaska Pipeline System led to an oil boom.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Royalty revenues from oil have funded large state budgets from 1980 onward.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Oil production was not the only economic value of Alaska's land.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Alaska discovered tourism as an important source of revenue.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Tourism became popular after World War II when military personnel stationed in the region returned home praising its natural splendor.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Alcan Highway, built during the war, and the Alaska Marine Highway System, completed in 1963, made the state more accessible than before.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Tourism has become increasingly important in Alaska, and today more than 1.4 million people visit the state each year.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] With tourism more vital to the economy, environmentalism rose in importance.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Because of the Act, Alaska now contains two-thirds of all American national parklands.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Today, more than half of Alaskan land is owned by the Federal Government.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 1989, the *Exxon Valdez* hit a reef in the Prince William Sound, spilling more than 11 million gallons (42 megalitres) of crude oil over 1,100 miles (1,800 km) of coastline.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Today, the battle between philosophies of development and conservation is seen in the contentious debate over oil drilling in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge and the proposed Pebble Mine.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Located at the northwest corner of North America very near to Asia, Alaska is the northernmost and westernmost state in the United States, but also has the most easterly longitude in the United States because the Aleutian Islands extend into the Eastern Hemisphere.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska is the only non-contiguous U.S. state on continental North America; about 500 miles (800 km) of Canadian territory consisting of British Columbia (in Canada) separates Alaska from Washington.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] It is technically part of the continental U.S., but is not usually included in the colloquial use of the term; Alaska is not part of the contiguous U.S., often called "the Lower 48".
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The capital city, Juneau, is situated on the mainland of the North American continent but is not connected by road to the rest of the North American highway system.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The largest lake in Alaska is Lake Illiamna.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska is bordered by Canada's Yukon and British Columbia to the east (making it the only state to border only a Canadian territory); the Gulf of Alaska and the Pacific Ocean to the south and southwest; the Bering Sea, Bering Strait, and Chukchi Sea to the west; and the Arctic Ocean to the north.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska's territorial waters touch Russia's territorial waters in the Bering Strait, as the Russian Big Diomede Island and Alaskan Little Diomede Island are only 3 miles (4.8 km) apart.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska has a longer coastline than all the other U.S. states combined.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] At 663,268 square miles (1,717,856 km2) in total area, Alaska is by far the largest state in the United States.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska is more than twice the size of the second-largest U.S. state (Texas), and it is larger than the next three largest states (Texas, California, and Montana) combined.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska is the seventh largest subnational division in the world.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] If it was an independent nation, it would be the 18th largest country in the world; almost the same size as Iran.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] With its myriad islands, Alaska has nearly 34,000 miles (55,000 km) of tidal shoreline.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Aleutian Islands chain extends west from the southern tip of the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Many active volcanoes are found in the Aleutians and in coastal regions.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Unimak Island, for example, is home to Mount Shishaldin, which is an occasionally smoldering volcano that rises to 10,000 feet (3,000 m) above the North Pacific.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The chain of volcanoes extends to Mount Spurr, west of Anchorage on the mainland.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Geologists have identified Alaska as part of Wrangellia, a large region consisting of multiple states and Canadian provinces in the Pacific Northwest, which is actively undergoing continent building.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] One of the world's largest tides occurs in Turnagain Arm, just south of Anchorage, where tidal differences can be more than 35 feet (10.7 m).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska has more than 409,000 natural lakes at least one hectare or bigger.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Marshlands and wetland permafrost cover 188,320 square miles (487,700 km2) (mostly in northern, western and southwest flatlands).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Glacier ice covers about 28,957 square miles (75,000 km2) of Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Bering Glacier is the largest glacier in North America, covering 2,008 square miles (5,200 km2) alone.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The most populous region of Alaska contains Anchorage, the Matanuska-Susitna Valley and the Kenai Peninsula.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Rural, mostly unpopulated areas south of the Alaska Range and west of the Wrangell Mountains also fall within the definition of South Central, as do the Prince William Sound area and the communities of Cordova and Valdez.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Also referred to as the Panhandle or Inside Passage, this is the region of Alaska closest to the contiguous states.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] As such, this was where most of the initial non-indigenous settlement occurred in the years following the Alaska Purchase.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The region is dominated by the Alexander Archipelago as well as the Tongass National Forest, the largest national forest in the United States.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] It contains the state capital Juneau, the former capital Sitka, and Ketchikan, at one time Alaska's largest city.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Alaska Marine Highway provides a vital surface transportation link throughout the area and country, as only three communities (Haines, Hyder and Skagway) enjoy direct connections to the contiguous North American road system.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Interior is the largest region of Alaska; much of it is uninhabited wilderness.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Fairbanks is the only large city in the region.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Denali National Park and Preserve is located here.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Denali, federally designated as Mount McKinley, is the highest mountain in North America and is also located here.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The North Slope is mostly tundra peppered with small villages.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The area is known for its massive reserves of crude oil and contains both the National Petroleum Reserve–Alaska and the Prudhoe Bay Oil Field.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The city of Utqiaġvik, formerly known as Barrow, is the northernmost city in the United States and is located here.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Northwest Arctic area, anchored by Kotzebue and also containing the Kobuk River valley, is often considered part of this region.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The respective Inupiat of the North Slope and of the Northwest Arctic seldom consider themselves to be one people.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Southwest Alaska is a sparsely inhabited region stretching some 500 miles (800 km) inland from the Bering Sea.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Most of the population lives along the coast.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Kodiak Island is also located in the Southwest.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The massive Yukon–Kuskokwim Delta, one of the largest river deltas in the world, is here.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Portions of the Alaska Peninsula are considered part of the Southwest, with the Aleutian Islands often (but not always) being grouped in as well.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] While primarily part of Southwest Alaska when grouped economically, the Aleutian islands are sometimes recognized as an alternate group from the rest of the region due to the geographic separation from the continent.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] More than 300 small volcanic islands make up this chain, which stretches more than 1,200 miles (1,900 km) into the Pacific Ocean.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Some of these islands fall in the Eastern Hemisphere, but the International Date Line was drawn west of 180° to keep the whole state, and thus the entire North American continent, within the same legal day.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Two of the islands, Attu and Kiska, were occupied by Japanese forces during World War II.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] As of 2023 the United States Bureau of Land Management manages 290 million surface and subsurface acres as public lands, including a multitude of national forests, national parks, national wildlife refuges, and federal mineral estate land.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Of these, the Bureau of Land Management manages 87 million acres (35 million hectares), or 23.8% of the state.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Arctic National Wildlife Refuge is managed by the United States Fish and Wildlife Service.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] It is the world's largest wildlife refuge, comprising 16 million acres (6.5 million hectares).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Of the remaining land area, the state of Alaska owns 101 million acres (41 million hectares), its entitlement under the Alaska Statehood Act.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] A portion of that acreage is occasionally ceded to the organized boroughs presented above, under the statutory provisions pertaining to newly formed boroughs.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Smaller portions are set aside for rural subdivisions and other homesteading-related opportunities.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] These are not very popular due to the often remote and roadless locations.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The University of Alaska, as a land grant university, also owns substantial acreage which it manages independently.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Another 44 million acres (18 million hectares) are owned by 12 regional, and scores of local, Native corporations created under the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (ANCSA) of 1971.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Regional Native corporation Doyon, Limited often promotes itself as the largest private landowner in Alaska in advertisements and other communications.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Provisions of ANCSA allowing the corporations' land holdings to be sold on the open market starting in 1991 were repealed before they could take effect.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Effectively, the corporations hold title (including subsurface title in many cases, a privilege denied to individual Alaskans) but cannot sell the land.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Individual Native allotments are sold on the open market.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Various private interests own the remaining land, totaling about one percent of the state.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska is, by a large margin, the state with the smallest percentage of private land ownership when Native corporation holdings are excluded.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Alaska Heritage Resources Survey (AHRS) is a restricted inventory of all reported historic and prehistoric sites within the U.S. state of Alaska; it is maintained by the Office of History and Archaeology.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The survey's inventory of cultural resources includes objects, structures, buildings, sites, districts, and travel ways, with a general provision that they are more than fifty years old.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] As of 31 January 2012, more than 35,000 sites have been reported.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Unlike most of U.S. states, Alaska is not divided into counties.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Similarly to Louisiana's parishes, it is divided into *boroughs*.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Delegates to the Alaska Constitutional Convention wanted to avoid the pitfalls of the traditional county system and adopted their own unique model.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Many of the more densely populated parts of the state are part of Alaska's 16 boroughs, which function somewhat similarly to counties in other states.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Unlike county-equivalents in the other states, the boroughs do not cover the state's entire land area.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The area not part of any borough is referred to as the Unorganized Borough.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Unorganized Borough has no government of its own, but the U.S.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Census Bureau in cooperation with the state divided the Unorganized Borough into 11 census areas solely for the purposes of statistical analysis and presentation.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] A *recording district* is a mechanism for management of the public record in Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The state is divided into 34 recording districts which are centrally administered under a state recorder.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] All recording districts use the same acceptance criteria, fee schedule, etc., for accepting documents into the public record.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Whereas many U.S. states use a three-tiered system of decentralization—state/county/township—most of Alaska uses two tiers—state/borough.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Owing to the low population density, most of the land is located in the Unorganized Borough.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] As the name implies, it has no intermediate borough government but is administered directly by the state government.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 2000, 57.71% of Alaska's area has this status, with 13.05% of the population.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 1975, Anchorage merged the city government with the Greater Anchorage Area Borough to form the Municipality of Anchorage, containing the city proper and the communities of Eagle River, Chugiak, Peters Creek, Girdwood, Bird, and Indian.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Fairbanks has a separate borough (the Fairbanks North Star Borough) and municipality (the City of Fairbanks).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska's most populous city is Anchorage, home to 291,247 people in 2020.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The richest location in Alaska by per capita income is Denali ($42,245).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Yakutat, Sitka, Juneau, and Anchorage are the four largest cities in the U.S. by area.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In the 2020 United States census, Alaska has 355 incorporated cities and census-designated places (CDPs).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The tally of cities includes four unified municipalities, essentially the equivalent of a consolidated city–county.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The majority of these communities are located in the rural expanse of Alaska known as "The Bush" and are unconnected to that contiguous North American road network.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The table at the bottom of this section lists the 100 largest cities and census-designated places in Alaska, in population order.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Of Alaska's 2020 U.S. census population figure of 733,391, 16,655 people, or 2.27% of the population, did not live in an incorporated city or census-designated place.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Approximately three-quarters of that figure were people who live in urban and suburban neighborhoods on the outskirts of the city limits of Ketchikan, Kodiak, Palmer and Wasilla.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] CDPs have not been established for these areas by the United States Census Bureau.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Seven CDPs were established for the Ketchikan-area neighborhoods in the 1980 census (Clover Pass, Herring Cove, Ketchikan East, Mountain Point, Alaska Route 7, Pennock Island and Saxman East), but have not been used since.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The remaining population was scattered throughout Alaska, both within organized boroughs and in the Unorganized Borough, in largely remote areas.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska is the coldest state in the United States.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The climate in the south and southeastern Alaska is a mid-latitude oceanic climate (Köppen climate classification: *Cfb*), and a subarctic oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfc*) in the northern parts, with cool summers and relatively mild winters.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] On an annual basis, the southeast is both the wettest and warmest part of Alaska with milder temperatures in the winter and high precipitation throughout the year.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Juneau averages over 50 in (130 cm) of precipitation a year, and Ketchikan averages over 150 in (380 cm).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] This is also the only region in Alaska in which the average daytime high temperature is above freezing during the winter months.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The climate of Anchorage and south central Alaska is mild by Alaskan standards due to the region's proximity to the seacoast.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] While the area gets less rain than southeast Alaska, it gets more snow, and days tend to be clearer.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] On average, Anchorage receives 16 in (41 cm) of precipitation a year, with around 75 in (190 cm) of snow, although there are areas in the south central which receive far more snow.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] It is a subarctic climate (Köppen: *Dfc*) due to its brief, cool summers.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The climate of western Alaska is determined in large part by the Bering Sea and the Gulf of Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] It is a subarctic oceanic climate in the southwest and a continental subarctic climate farther north.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The temperature is somewhat moderate considering how far north the area is.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] This region has a tremendous amount of variety in precipitation.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] An area stretching from the northern side of the Seward Peninsula to the Kobuk River valley (i.e., the region around Kotzebue Sound) is technically a desert, with portions receiving less than 10 in (25 cm) of precipitation annually.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] On the other extreme, some locations between Dillingham and Bethel average around 100 in (250 cm) of precipitation.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The climate of the interior of Alaska is subarctic and is a classic example of a continental subarctic climate, except in a few valleys where the climate approaches humid continental (Köppen: *Dfb*).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Some of the highest and lowest temperatures in Alaska occur around the area near Fairbanks.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Summers are warm, albeit generally short, and may have temperatures reaching into the 90s °F (the low-to-mid 30s °C).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In the long and very cold winters, the temperature can fall below −60 °F (−51 °C).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Precipitation is sparse in the Interior, often less than 10 in (25 cm) a year, but what precipitation falls in the winter tends to stay the entire winter.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The highest and lowest recorded temperatures in Alaska are both in the Interior.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The highest is 100 °F (38 °C) in Fort Yukon, which is just 8 mi or 13 km inside the arctic circle, on June 27, 1915, making Alaska tied with Hawaii as the state with the lowest high temperature in the United States.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The lowest official Alaska temperature is −80 °F (−62 °C) in Prospect Creek on January 23, 1971, one degree above the lowest temperature recorded in continental North America (in Snag, Yukon, Canada).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The climate in the extreme north of Alaska, north of the Brooks Range, is Arctic (Köppen: *ET*) with long, very cold winters and short, cool summers.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Even in July, the average low temperature in Utqiaġvik is 34 °F (1 °C).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Precipitation is light in this part of Alaska, with many places averaging less than 10 in (25 cm) per year, mostly as snow which stays on the ground almost the entire year.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The United States Census Bureau found in the 2020 United States census that the population of Alaska was 733,391 on April 1, 2020, a 3.3% increase since the 2010 United States census.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In the 2010 United States Census, Alaska had a population of 710,231, an increase of 13.3%, up from 626,932 at the 2000 U.S. census.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 2020, Alaska ranked as the 48th largest state by population, ahead of only Vermont and Wyoming.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska is the least densely populated state, and one of the most sparsely populated areas in the world, at 1.2 inhabitants per square mile (0.46/km2).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The next state, Wyoming, has 5.8 inhabitants per square mile (2.2/km2).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska is by far the largest U.S. state by area, and the tenth wealthiest, per capita income.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] As of 2018 due to its population size, it is one of 14 U.S. states that still have only one telephone area code.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 2,320 homeless people in Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The 2019 American Community Survey estimated 60.2% of the population was white, 3.7% black or African American, 15.6% American Indian or Alaska Native, 6.5% Asian, 1.4% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 7.5% two or more races, and 7.3% Hispanic or Latin American.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] At the survey estimates, 7.8% of the total population was foreign-born from 2015 to 2019.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 2015, 61.3% were white, 3.4% black or African American, 13.3% American Indian or Alaska Native, 6.2% Asian, 0.9% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 0.3% some other race, and 7.7% multiracial.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Hispanics and Latin Americans were 7% of the state population in 2015.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] From 2015 to 2019, the largest Hispanic and Latin American groups were Mexican Americans, Puerto Ricans, and Cuban Americans.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The largest Asian groups living in the state were Filipinos, Korean Americans, and Japanese and Chinese Americans.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 2010, Alaska was 64.1% white, 14.8% American Indian and Alaska Native, 5.4% Asian, 3.3% black or African American, 1.0% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 1.6% from some other race, and 7.3% from two or more races in 2010.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Hispanics or Latin Americans made up 5.5% of the population in 2010.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] As of 2011, 50.7% of Alaska's population younger than one year of age belonged to minority groups (i.e., did not have two parents of white ancestry).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 1960, the United States Census Bureau reported Alaska's population as 77.2% white, 3% black, and 18.8% American Indian and Alaska Native.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 2018, the top countries of origin for Alaska's immigrants were the Philippines, Mexico, Canada, Thailand and South Korea.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In the 2011 American Community Survey, 83.4% of people over the age of five spoke only English at home.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] About 3.5% spoke Spanish at home, 2.2% spoke another Indo-European language, about 4.3% spoke an Asian language (including Tagalog), and about 5.3% spoke other languages at home.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 2019, the American Community Survey determined 83.7% spoke only English, and 16.3% spoke another language other than English.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The most spoken European language after English was Spanish, spoken by approximately 4.0% of the state population.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Collectively, Asian and Pacific Islander languages were spoken by 5.6% of Alaskans.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Since 2010, 5.2% of Alaskans speak one of the state's 20 Indigenous languages, known locally as "Native languages".
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska is also known for a distinctive dialect of Russian, named Alaskan Russian.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Alaska Native Language Center at the University of Alaska Fairbanks claims that at least twenty Alaska Native languages exist and there are also some languages with different dialects.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Most of Alaska's Native languages belong to either the Eskimo–Aleut or Na-Dene language families.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Some languages are thought to be isolates (e.g., Haida) or have not yet been classified (e.g., Tsimshianic).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 2014, nearly all of Alaska's Native languages were classified as either threatened, shifting, moribund, nearly extinct, or dormant languages.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In October 2014, the governor of Alaska signed a bill declaring the state's 20 Indigenous languages to have official status.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] This bill gave them symbolic recognition as official languages, though they have not been adopted for official use within the government.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In May 2024, a bill replaced Tanana with Middle Tanana and Lower Tanana, added Cupʼig and Wetał.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Multiple surveys have ranked Alaska among the most irreligious states.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] ChangePoint in south Anchorage (left) and Anchorage Baptist Temple in east Anchorage are Alaska's largest churches in terms of attendance and membership.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 2010, per the Association of Religion Data Archives (ARDA), about 34% of Alaska residents were members of religious congregations.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Of the religious population, roughly 4% were Mormon, 0.5% Jewish, 0.5% Muslim, 1% Buddhist, 0.2% Baháʼí, and 0.5% Hindu.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 2010, the largest religious denominations in Alaska were the Catholic Church with 50,866 adherents; non-denominational Evangelicals with 38,070 adherents; The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints with 32,170 adherents; and the Southern Baptist Convention with 19,891 adherents.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska has been identified, along with Washington and Oregon in the Pacific Northwest, as being the least religious states in the United States, in terms of church membership.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Pew Research Center in 2014 determined 62% of the adult population practiced Christianity.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Of the Christian denominations, Catholicism was the largest Christian group.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] When Protestant denominations were combined, Protestantism was the largest Christian tradition, with Evangelicalism being the largest movement within the Protestant group.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The unaffiliated population made up the largest non-Christian religious affiliation at 37%.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Atheists made up 5% of the population and the largest non-Christian religion was Buddhism.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 2020, the Public Religion Research Institute (PRRI) determined 57% of adults were Christian.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] By 2022, Christianity increased to 77% of the population according to the PRRI.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Through the Association of Religion Data Archives in 2020, its Christian population was dominated by non/inter-denominational Protestantism as the single largest Christian cohort, with 73,930 adherents.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Roman Catholics were second with 40,280 members; throughout its Christian population, non-denominational Christians had an adherence rate of 100.81 per 1,000 residents, and Catholics 54.92 per 1,000 residents.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Per 2014's Pew study, religion was seen as very important to 41% of the population, although 29% considered it somewhat important.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 2014, Pew determined roughly 55% believed in God with absolute certainty, and 24% believed fairly certainly.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Reflecting the separate 2020 ARDA study, the 2014 Pew study showed 30% attended religious services once a week, 34% once or twice a month, and 36% seldom/never.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 1795, the first Russian Orthodox Church was established in Kodiak.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Intermarriage with Alaska Natives helped the Russian immigrants integrate into society.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] As a result, an increasing number of Russian Orthodox churches gradually became established within Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaska also has the largest Quaker population (by percentage) of any state.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 2009, there were 6,000 Jews in Alaska, for whom observance of halakha may pose special problems.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Alaskan Hindus often share venues and celebrations with members of other Asian religious communities, including Sikhs and Jains.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 2010, Alaskan Hindus established the Sri Ganesha Temple of Alaska, making it the first Hindu Temple in Alaska and the northernmost Hindu Temple in the world.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] There are an estimated 2,000–3,000 Hindus in Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The vast majority of Hindus live in Anchorage or Fairbanks.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Estimates for the number of Muslims in Alaska range from 2,000 to 5,000.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] In 2020, ARDA estimated there were 400 Muslims in the state.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] The Islamic Community Center of Anchorage began efforts in the late 1990s to construct a mosque in Anchorage.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] They broke ground on a building in south Anchorage in 2010 and were nearing completion in late 2014.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] When completed, the mosque was the first in the state and one of the northernmost mosques in the world.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] There is also a Baháʼí center, and there were 690 adherents in 2020.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p01] Additionally, there were 469 adherents of Hinduism and Yoga altogether in 2020, and a small number of Buddhists were present.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In October 2022, Alaska had a total employment of 316,900.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The number of employer establishments was 21,077.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] As of August 2025, the unemployment rate was 4.7%.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The state's historically lowest unemployment rate was recorded in August 2022 at 3.8%, and its highest in May 2020 at 11.7%.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Bureau of Economic Analysis, Alaska's gross state product was $75.011 billion in 2025.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Its per capita personal income was $80,175 in 2025.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] According to a 2013 study by Phoenix Marketing International, Alaska had the fifth-largest number of millionaires per capita in the United States, with a ratio of 6.75 percent.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The oil and gas industry dominates the Alaskan economy, with more than 80% of the state's revenues derived from petroleum extraction.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska's main export product, excluding oil and natural gas, is seafood, primarily salmon, cod, pollock and crab.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Agriculture represents a minuscule fraction of the Alaskan economy.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Agricultural production is primarily for consumption within the state and includes nursery stock, dairy products, vegetables, and livestock.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Manufacturing is limited, with most foodstuffs and general goods imported from elsewhere.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Employment is primarily in government and industries such as natural resource extraction, shipping, and transportation.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Military bases are a significant component of the economy in Anchorage and the Fairbanks North Star and Kodiak Island boroughs.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In 2025, 99.1% of Alaska businesses are small businesses and employ 54.2% of the state's workforce.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Federal subsidies are also an important part of the economy, allowing the state to keep taxes low.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Its industrial outputs are crude petroleum, natural gas, coal, gold, precious metals, zinc and other mining, seafood processing, timber and wood products.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] There is also a growing service and tourism sector.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Tourists have contributed to the economy by supporting local lodging.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska has vast energy resources, although its oil reserves have been largely depleted.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Major oil and gas reserves were found in the Alaska North Slope (ANS) and Cook Inlet basins, but according to the Energy Information Administration, by February 2014 Alaska had fallen to fourth place in the nation in crude oil production after Texas, North Dakota, and California.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Prudhoe Bay on Alaska's North Slope is still the second highest-yielding oil field in the United States, typically producing about 400,000 barrels per day (64,000 m3/d), although by early 2014 North Dakota's Bakken Formation was producing over 900,000 barrels per day (140,000 m3/d).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Trans-Alaska Pipeline can transport and pump up to 2.1 million barrels (330,000 m3) of crude oil per day, more than any other crude oil pipeline in the United States.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Substantial coal deposits are found in Alaska's bituminous, sub-bituminous, and lignite coal basins.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The United States Geological Survey estimates that there are 85.4 trillion cubic feet (2,420 km3) of undiscovered, technically recoverable gas from natural gas hydrates on the Alaskan North Slope.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska also offers some of the highest hydroelectric power potential in the country from its numerous rivers.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Large swaths of the Alaskan coastline offer wind and geothermal energy potential as well.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska's economy depends heavily on increasingly expensive diesel fuel for heating, transportation, electric power and light.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Although wind and hydroelectric power are abundant and underdeveloped, proposals for statewide energy systems were judged uneconomical (at the time of the report, 2001) due to low (less than 50¢/gal) fuel prices, long distances and low population.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Alaska Permanent Fund is a constitutionally authorized appropriation of oil revenues, established by voters in 1976 to manage a surplus in state petroleum revenues from oil, largely in anticipation of the then recently constructed Trans-Alaska Pipeline System.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The fund was originally proposed by Governor Keith Miller on the eve of the 1969 Prudhoe Bay lease sale, out of fear that the legislature would spend the entire proceeds of the sale (which amounted to $900 million) at once.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] It was later championed by Governor Jay Hammond and Kenai state representative Hugh Malone.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] It has served as an attractive political prospect ever since, diverting revenues which would normally be deposited into the general fund.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Alaska Constitution was written so as to discourage dedicating state funds for a particular purpose.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Permanent Fund has become the rare exception to this, mostly due to the political climate of distrust existing during the time of its creation.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] From its initial principal of $734,000, the fund has grown to $50 billion as a result of oil royalties and capital investment programs.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Most if not all the principal is invested conservatively outside Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] This has led to frequent calls by Alaskan politicians for the Fund to make investments within Alaska, though such a stance has never gained momentum.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Every year, the state legislature takes out 8% from the earnings, puts 3% back into the principal for inflation proofing, and the remaining 5% is distributed to all qualifying Alaskans.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Permanent Fund is often considered to be one of the leading examples of a basic income policy in the world.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The cost of goods in Alaska has long been higher than in the contiguous 48 states.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Federal government employees, particularly United States Postal Service (USPS) workers and active-duty military members, receive a Cost of Living Allowance usually set at 25% of base pay because, while the cost of living has gone down, it is still one of the highest in the country.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Rural Alaska suffers from severely high prices for food and consumer goods compared to the rest of the country, due to the relatively limited transportation infrastructure.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Due to the northern climate and short growing season, relatively little farming occurs in Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Most farms are in either the Matanuska Valley, about 40 miles (64 km) northeast of Anchorage, or on the Kenai Peninsula, about 60 miles (97 km) southwest of Anchorage.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The short 100-day growing season limits the crops that can be grown, but the long sunny summer days make for productive growing seasons.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The primary crops are potatoes, carrots, lettuce, and cabbage.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Tanana Valley is another notable agricultural locus, especially the Delta Junction area, about 100 miles (160 km) southeast of Fairbanks, with a sizable concentration of farms growing agronomic crops; these farms mostly lie north and east of Fort Greely.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] This area was largely set aside and developed under a state program spearheaded by Hammond during his second term as governor.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Delta-area crops consist predominantly of barley and hay.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] West of Fairbanks lies another concentration of small farms catering to restaurants, the hotel and tourist industry, and community-supported agriculture.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaskan agriculture has experienced a surge in growth of market gardeners, small farms and farmers' markets in recent years, with the highest percentage increase (46%) in the nation in growth in farmers' markets in 2011, compared to 17% nationwide.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The peony industry has also taken off, as the growing season allows farmers to harvest during a gap in supply elsewhere in the world, thereby filling a niche in the flower market.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska, with no counties, lacks county fairs.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Instead, a small assortment of state and local fairs (with the Alaska State Fair in Palmer the largest), are held mostly in the late summer.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The fairs are mostly located in communities with historic or current agricultural activity, and feature local farmers exhibiting produce in addition to more high-profile commercial activities such as carnival rides, concerts and food.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] "Alaska Grown" is used as an agricultural slogan.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska has an abundance of seafood, with the primary fisheries in the Bering Sea and the North Pacific.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Seafood is one of the few food items that is often cheaper within the state than outside it.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Many Alaskans take advantage of salmon seasons to harvest portions of their household diet while fishing for subsistence, as well as sport.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] This includes fish taken by hook, net or wheel.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Hunting for subsistence, primarily caribou, moose, and Dall sheep is still common in the state, particularly in remote Bush communities.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] An example of a traditional native food is Akutaq, the Eskimo ice cream, which can consist of reindeer fat, seal oil, dried fish meat and local berries.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska's reindeer herding is concentrated on Seward Peninsula, where wild caribou can be prevented from mingling and migrating with the domesticated reindeer.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Most food in Alaska is transported into the state from "Outside" (the other 49 U.S. states), and shipping costs make food in the cities relatively expensive.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In rural areas, subsistence hunting and gathering is an essential activity because imported food is prohibitively expensive.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Although most small towns and villages in Alaska lie along the coastline, the cost of importing food to remote villages can be high because of the terrain and difficult road conditions, which change dramatically due to varying climate and precipitation changes.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Transport costs can reach 50¢ per pound ($1.10/kg) or higher in some remote areas during times of inclement weather or rough terrain conditions, if these locations can be reached at all.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The cost of delivering a gallon (3.8 L) of milk is about $3.50 in many villages where per capita income can be $20,000 or less.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Fuel cost per gallon is routinely twenty to thirty cents higher than the contiguous United States average, with only Hawaii having higher prices.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Some of Alaska's popular annual events are the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race from Anchorage to Nome, World Ice Art Championships in Fairbanks, the Blueberry Festival and Alaska Hummingbird Festival in Ketchikan, the Sitka Whale Fest, and the Stikine River Garnet Fest in Wrangell.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Stikine River attracts the largest springtime concentration of American bald eagles in the world.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Alaska Native Heritage Center celebrates the rich heritage of Alaska's 11 cultural groups.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Their purpose is to encourage cross-cultural exchanges among all people and enhance self-esteem among Native people.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Alaska Native Arts Foundation promotes and markets Native art from all regions and cultures in the State, using the internet.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Influences on music in Alaska include the traditional music of Alaska Natives as well as folk music brought by later immigrants from Russia and Europe.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Prominent musicians from Alaska include singer Jewel, traditional Aleut flautist Mary Youngblood, folk singer-songwriter Libby Roderick, Christian music singer-songwriter Lincoln Brewster, metal/post hardcore band 36 Crazyfists and the groups Pamyua and Portugal.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] There are many established music festivals in Alaska, including the Alaska Folk Festival, the Fairbanks Summer Arts Festival, the Anchorage Folk Festival, the Athabascan Old-Time Fiddling Festival, the Sitka Jazz Festival, the Sitka Summer Music Festival, and the Anchorage Chamber Music Festival.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The most prominent orchestra in Alaska is the Anchorage Symphony Orchestra, though the Fairbanks Symphony Orchestra and Juneau Symphony are also notable.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Anchorage Opera is currently the state's only professional opera company, though there are several volunteer and semi-professional organizations in the state as well.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The official state song of Alaska is "Alaska's Flag", which was adopted in 1955; it celebrates the flag of Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The 1983 Disney movie *Never Cry Wolf* was at least partially shot in Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The 1991 film *White Fang*, based on Jack London's 1906 novel and starring Ethan Hawke, was filmed in and around Haines.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Steven Seagal's 1994 *On Deadly Ground*, starring Michael Caine, was filmed in part at the Worthington Glacier near Valdez.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Many reality television shows are filmed in Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In 2011, the *Anchorage Daily News* found ten set in the state.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The following is a list of sporting venues, events, and teams based in Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Alaska State Troopers are Alaska's statewide police force.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] They have a long and storied history, but were not an official organization until 1941.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Before the force was officially organized, law enforcement in Alaska was handled by various federal agencies.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Larger towns usually have their own local police and some villages rely on "Public Safety Officers" who have police training but do not carry firearms.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In much of the state, the troopers serve as the only police force available.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In addition to enforcing traffic and criminal law, wildlife Troopers enforce hunting and fishing regulations.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Due to the varied terrain and wide scope of the Troopers' duties, they employ a wide variety of land, air, and water patrol vehicles.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Many rural communities in Alaska are considered "dry", having outlawed the importation of alcoholic beverages.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Suicide rates for rural residents are higher than urban rates.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Domestic abuse and other violent crimes are at high levels in Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] This is in part linked to alcohol abuse.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska has the highest rate of sexual assault in the nation, especially in rural areas.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The average age of sexually assaulted victims is 16 years old.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In four out of five cases, the suspects were relatives, friends, or acquaintances.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] As of 2022, CVS Health and Premera account for 47% and 46% of private health insurance, respectively.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Premera and Moda Health offer insurance on the federally-run Affordable Care Exchange.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Providence Alaska Medical Center in Anchorage is the largest hospital in the state as of 2021; Anchorage also hosts Alaska Regional Hospital and Alaska Native Medical Center.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska's other major cities such as Fairbanks and Juneau also have local hospitals.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In Southeast Alaska, Southeast Alaska Regional Health Consortium, runs healthcare facilities across 27 communities as of 2022, including hospitals in Sitka and Wrangell; although it originally served Native Americans only, it has expanded access and combined with other local facilities over time.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Alaska Department of Education and Early Development administers many school districts in Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In addition, the state operates a boarding school, Mt.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Edgecumbe High School in Sitka, and provides partial funding for other boarding schools, including Nenana Student Living Center in Nenana and The Galena Interior Learning Academy in Galena.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] There are more than a dozen colleges and universities in Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Accredited universities in Alaska include the University of Alaska Anchorage, University of Alaska Fairbanks, University of Alaska Southeast, and Alaska Pacific University.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska is the only state that has no collegiate athletic programs that are members of NCAA Division I, although both Alaska-Fairbanks and Alaska-Anchorage maintain single sport membership in Division I for men's ice hockey.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development operates AVTEC, Alaska's Institute of Technology.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Campuses in Seward and Anchorage offer one-week to 11-month training programs in areas as diverse as Information Technology, Welding, Nursing, and Mechanics.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska has had a problem with a "brain drain".
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Many of its young people, including most of the highest academic achievers, leave the state after high school graduation and do not return.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] As of 2013 Alaska did not have a law school or medical school.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The University of Alaska has attempted to combat this by offering partial four-year scholarships to the top 10% of Alaska high school graduates, via the Alaska Scholars Program.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Beginning in 1998, schools in rural Alaska must have at least ten students to retain funding from the state, and campuses not meeting the number close.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] This was due to the loss in oil revenues that previously propped up smaller rural schools.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In 2015, there was a proposal to raise that minimum to 25, but legislators in the state largely did not agree.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska has few road connections compared to the rest of the U.S.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The state's road system, covering a relatively small area of the state, linking the central population centers and the Alaska Highway, the principal route out of the state through Canada.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The state capital, Juneau, is not accessible by road, with access only by ferry or flight; this has spurred debate over decades about moving the capital to a city on the road system, or building a road connection from Haines.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The western part of Alaska has no road system connecting the communities with the rest of Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Interstate Highways in Alaska consists of a total of 1,082 miles (1,741 km).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] These are mostly not built to Interstate Highway standards and their status as such is largely notional.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] A unique feature of the Alaska Highway system is the Anton Anderson Memorial Tunnel, an active Alaska Railroad tunnel that provides a paved roadway link with the isolated community of Whittier on Prince William Sound to the Seward Highway about 50 miles (80 km) southeast of Anchorage at Portage.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] At 2.5 miles (4.0 km), the tunnel was the longest road tunnel in North America until 2007.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The tunnel is the longest combination road and rail tunnel in North America.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Southwest Alaska is largely coastal, sparsely populated, and unconnected to the road system.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Access to most communities in Southwest Alaska is primarily by air taxi, although larger towns like Kodiak, Bethel, King Salmon, Dillingham, and Dutch Harbor are accessible by scheduled air service.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Some coastal communities can be reached via the Alaska Marine Highway ferry.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Built around 1915, the Alaska Railroad (ARR) played a key role in the development of Alaska through the 20th century.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] It links shipping lanes on the North Pacific with Interior Alaska with tracks that run from Seward by way of South Central Alaska, passing through Anchorage, Eklutna, Wasilla, Talkeetna, Denali, and Fairbanks, with spurs to Whittier, Palmer and North Pole.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The cities, towns, villages, and region served by ARR tracks are known statewide as "The Railbelt".
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In recent years, the ever-improving paved highway system began to eclipse the railroad's importance in Alaska's economy.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The railroad played a vital role in Alaska's development, moving freight into Alaska while transporting natural resources southward, such as coal from the Usibelli coal mine near Healy to Seward and gravel from the Matanuska Valley to Anchorage.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] It is well known for its summertime tour passenger service.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Alaska Railroad was one of the last railroads in North America to use cabooses in regular service and still uses them on some gravel trains.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] It continues to offer one of the last flag stop routes in the country.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] A stretch of about 60 miles (100 km) of track along an area north of Talkeetna remains inaccessible by road; the railroad provides the only transportation to rural homes and cabins in the area.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Until construction of the Parks Highway in the 1970s, the railroad provided the only land access to most of the region along its entire route.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In northern Southeast Alaska, the White Pass and Yukon Route also partly runs through the state from Skagway northwards into Canada (British Columbia and Yukon Territory), crossing the border at White Pass Summit.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] This line is now mainly used by tourists, often arriving by cruise liner at Skagway.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] It was featured in the 1983 BBC television series *Great Little Railways*.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] These two railroads are connected neither to each other nor any other railroad.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The nearest link to the North American railway network is the northwest terminus of the Canadian National Railway at Prince Rupert, British Columbia, several hundred miles to the southeast.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Congress authorized $6 million to study the feasibility of a rail link between Alaska, Canada, and the lower 48.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] As of 2021 the Alaska-Alberta Railway Development Corporation is in receivership.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Some private companies provides car float service between Whittier and Seattle.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Many cities, towns, and villages in Alaska don't have road or highway access.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The only modes of access involve travel by air, river, or the sea.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska's well-developed state-owned ferry system, known as the Alaska Marine Highway, serves the cities of southeast, the Gulf Coast and the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The ferries transport vehicles and passengers.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The system also operates a ferry service from Bellingham, Washington and Prince Rupert, British Columbia, in Canada through the Inside Passage to Skagway.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Inter-Island Ferry Authority also serves as an important marine link for many communities in the Prince of Wales Island region of Southeast and works in concert with the Alaska Marine Highway.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In recent years, cruise lines have created a summertime tourism market, mainly connecting the Pacific Northwest to Southeast Alaska and, to a lesser degree, towns along Alaska's gulf coast.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The population of Ketchikan for example fluctuates dramatically on many days—up to four large cruise ships can dock there at the same time.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Cities not served by road, sea, or river can be reached only by air, foot, dogsled, or snowmachine, accounting for Alaska's extremely well developed bush air services—an Alaskan novelty.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Anchorage, and to a lesser extent Fairbanks, is served by many major airlines.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Because of limited highway access, air travel remains the most efficient form of transportation in and out of the state.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Anchorage recently completed extensive remodeling and construction at Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport to help accommodate the upsurge in tourism.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In 2012–2013, Alaska received almost two million visitors.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Making regular flights to most villages and towns within the state commercially viable is difficult, so they are heavily subsidized by the federal government through the Essential Air Service program.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The bulk of remaining commercial flight offerings come from small regional commuter airlines such as Ravn Alaska, PenAir, and Frontier Flying Service.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The smallest towns and villages must rely on scheduled or chartered bush flying services using general aviation aircraft such as the Cessna Caravan, the most popular aircraft in use in the state.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Much of this service can be attributed to the Alaska bypass mail program which subsidizes bulk mail delivery to Alaskan rural communities.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The program requires 70% of that subsidy to go to carriers who offer passenger service to the communities.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Many communities have small air taxi services.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] These operations originated from the demand for customized transport to remote areas.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Perhaps the most quintessentially Alaskan plane is the bush seaplane.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The world's busiest seaplane base is Lake Hood, located next to Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport, where flights bound for remote villages without an airstrip carry passengers, cargo, and many items from stores and warehouse clubs.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In 2006, Alaska had the highest number of pilots per capita of any U.S. state.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In Alaska there are 8,795 active pilot certificates as of 2020.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Another Alaskan transportation method is the dogsled.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In modern times, that is, any time after the mid- to late‑1920s, dog mushing is more of a sport than a true means of transportation.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Races are held around the state, but the best known is the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race, a 1,150-mile (1,850 km) trail from Anchorage to Nome, although the distance varies from year to year, the official distance is set at 1,049 miles or 1,688 km.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The race commemorates the famous 1925 serum run to Nome in which mushers and dogs like Togo and Balto took much-needed medicine to the diphtheria-stricken community of Nome when all other means of transportation had failed.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Mushers from all over the world come to Anchorage each March to compete for cash, prizes, and prestige.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The "Serum Run" is another sled dog race that more accurately follows the route of the famous 1925 relay, leaving from the community of Nenana, southwest of Fairbanks, to Nome.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In areas not served by road or rail, primary transportation in summer is by fourwheeler and in winter by snowmachine.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska's internet and other data transport systems are provided largely through the two major telecommunications companies: GCI and Alaska Communications.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] GCI owns and operates what it calls the Alaska United Fiber Optic system.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] As of late 2011, Alaska Communications had two fiber optic paths to the lower 48 and two more across Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In January 2011, it was reported that a $1 billion project to connect Asia and rural Alaska was being planned, aided in part by $350 million in stimulus from the federal government.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The state of Alaska employs approximately 16,000 people statewide.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Alaska State Legislature consists of a 40-member House of Representatives and a 20-member Senate.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Senators serve four-year terms and House members two.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The governor of Alaska serves four-year terms.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The lieutenant governor runs separately from the governor in the primaries, but during the general election, the nominee for governor and nominee for lieutenant governor run together on the same ticket.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska's court system has four levels: the Alaska Supreme Court, the Alaska Court of Appeals, the Superior Court and the district courts.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The superior and district courts are trial courts.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Superior courts are courts of general jurisdiction, while district courts hear only certain types of cases, including misdemeanor criminal cases and civil cases valued up to $100,000.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Supreme Court and the Court of Appeals are appellate courts.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Court of Appeals is required to hear appeals from certain lower-court decisions, including those regarding criminal prosecutions, juvenile delinquency, and habeas corpus.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Supreme Court hears civil appeals and may in its discretion hear criminal appeals.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Although in its early years of statehood Alaska was a Democratic state, since the early 1970s it has been characterized as Republican-leaning.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Local political communities have often worked on issues related to land use development, fishing, tourism, and individual rights.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska Natives, while organized in and around their communities, have been active within the Native corporations.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] These have been given ownership over large tracts of land, which require stewardship.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska was formerly the only state in which possession of one ounce or less of marijuana in one's home was completely legal under state law, though the federal law remains in force.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The state has an independence movement favoring a vote on secession from the United States, with the Alaskan Independence Party.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Six Republicans and four Democrats have served as governor of Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Republican governor Wally Hickel was elected to the office for a second term in 1990 after leaving the Republican party and briefly joining the Alaskan Independence Party ticket just long enough to be reelected.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] He rejoined the Republican party in 1994.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska's voter initiative making marijuana legal took effect in February 2015, placing Alaska alongside Colorado and Washington, as well as Washington D.C., as the first three U.S. states where recreational marijuana is legal.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The law means people over 21 can consume small amounts of cannabis.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The first legal marijuana store opened in Valdez in October 2016.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] To finance state government operations, Alaska depends primarily on petroleum revenues and federal subsidies.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] This allows it to have the lowest individual tax burden in the United States.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] It is one of five states with no sales tax, one of seven states with no individual income tax, and—along with New Hampshire—one of two that has neither.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Department of Revenue Tax Division reports regularly on the state's revenue sources.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The department issues an annual summary of its operations, including new state laws that directly affect the tax division.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In 2014, the Tax Foundation ranked Alaska as having the fourth most "business friendly" tax policy, behind only Wyoming, South Dakota, and Nevada.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] 89 municipalities collect a local sales tax, from 1.0 to 7.5%, typically 3–5%.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Other local taxes levied include raw fish taxes, hotel, motel, and bed-and-breakfast 'bed' taxes, severance taxes, liquor and tobacco taxes, gaming (pull tabs) taxes, tire taxes and fuel transfer taxes.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] A part of the revenue collected from certain state taxes and license fees, such as petroleum, aviation motor fuel, telephone cooperative, is shared with municipalities in Alaska.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The fall in oil prices after the fracking boom in the early 2010s has decimated Alaska's state treasury, which has historically received about 85 percent of its revenue from taxes and fees imposed on oil and gas companies.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The state government has had to drastically reduce its budget, and has brought its budget shortfall from over $2 billion in 2016 to under $500 million by 2018.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In 2020, Alaska's state government budget was $4.8 billion, while projected government revenues were only $4.5 billion.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska regularly supports Republicans in presidential elections and has done so since statehood.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Republicans have won the state's electoral college votes in all but one election that it has participated in (1964).
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] No state has voted for a Democratic presidential candidate fewer times.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska was carried by Democratic nominee Lyndon B.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Johnson during his landslide election in 1964, while the 1960 and 1968 elections were close.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Since 1972, Republicans have carried the state by large margins.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In 2008, Republican John McCain defeated Democrat Barack Obama in Alaska, 59.49% to 37.83%.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] McCain's running mate was Sarah Palin, the state's governor and the first Alaskan on a major party ticket.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Obama lost Alaska again in 2012, but he captured 40% of the state's vote in that election, making him the first Democrat to do so since 1968.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In 2020, Joe Biden received 42.77% of the vote for president, marking the high point for a Democratic presidential candidate since Johnson's 1964 victory.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Alaska Bush, central Juneau, midtown and downtown Anchorage, and the areas surrounding the University of Alaska Fairbanks campus and Ester have been strongholds of the Democratic Party.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The Matanuska-Susitna Borough, the Kenai Peninsula, the majority of Fairbanks (including North Pole and the military base), and South Anchorage typically have the strongest Republican showing.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Alaska has a history of primary defeats for incumbent U.S.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Senators, including Ernest Gruening, Mike Gravel, and Lisa Murkowski.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] However, Murkowski won re-election with a write-in campaign.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Despite this, Alaska has also seen long-serving members of Congress, such as Ted Stevens, who served as a U.S.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Senator for 40 years, and Don Young, who held Alaska's sole U.S.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] House seat for 49 years, from 1973 to 2022.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] In the 2020 election cycle, Alaskan voters approved Ballot Measure 2.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The measure passed by a margin of 1.1%, or about 4,000 votes.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The measure requires campaigns to disclose the original source and any intermediaries for campaign contributions over $2,000.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The measure also establishes non-partisan primaries, sometimes called jungle primaries, for statewide elections (like in Washington state and California) and ranked-choice voting, like in Maine.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] Measure 2 makes Alaska the third state with nonpartisan primaries for all statewide races, the second state with ranked choice voting, and the only state with both.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] The 2022 special election to fill Alaska's only U.S.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] House seat, left vacant by the death of Don Young, was won by Mary Peltola.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] She became the first Democrat to win the House seat since 1972 and the first Alaskan Native elected to the United States Congress in history.
[src:core-plug/alaska-p02] After winning a full term in the 2022 general election, Peltola lost reelection in 2024 to Republican Nick Begich III.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:core-plug/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] An **antifreeze** is an additive which lowers the freezing point of a water-based liquid.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] An antifreeze mixture is used to achieve freezing-point depression for cold environments.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Common antifreezes also increase the boiling point of the liquid, allowing higher coolant temperature.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] However, all common antifreeze additives also have lower heat capacities than water, and do reduce water's ability to act as a coolant when added to it.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Because water has good properties as a coolant, water plus antifreeze is used in internal combustion engines and other heat transfer applications, such as HVAC chillers and solar water heaters.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] The purpose of antifreeze is to prevent a rigid enclosure from bursting due to expansion when water freezes.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Commercially, both the *additive* (pure concentrate) and the *mixture* (diluted solution) are called antifreeze, depending on the context.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Careful selection of an antifreeze can enable a wide temperature range in which the mixture remains in the liquid phase, which is critical to efficient heat transfer and the proper functioning of heat exchangers.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Most if not all commercial antifreeze formulations intended for use in heat transfer applications include anti-corrosion and anti-cavitation agents (that protect the hydraulic circuit from progressive wear).
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Water was the original coolant for internal combustion engines.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] It is cheap, nontoxic, and has a high heat capacity.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] It however has only a 100 Kelvin liquid range, and it expands upon freezing.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] To address these problems, alternative coolants with improved properties were developed.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Freezing and boiling points are colligative properties of a solution, which depend on the concentration of dissolved substances.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Salts, for example, lower the melting points of aqueous solutions and as such are commonly used for de-icing due to their low cost.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] However, salt solutions typically cannot be used in cooling systems because they induce corrosion of metals.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Solutions of organic compounds, especially alcohols, in water are effective.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Alcohols such as methanol, ethanol, ethylene glycol, etc. have been the basis of all antifreezes since they were commercialized in the 1920s.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Most automotive engines are "water"-cooled to remove waste heat, though the "water" used is actually a mixture of water and antifreeze.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] The term **engine coolant** is widely used in the automotive industry, which covers its primary function of convective heat transfer for internal combustion engines.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] When used in an automotive context, corrosion inhibitors are added to help protect vehicles' radiators, which often contain a range of electrochemically incompatible metals (aluminum, cast iron, copper, brass, solder, etc.).
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Water pump seal lubricant is also added.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Antifreeze was developed to overcome the shortcomings of water as a heat transfer fluid.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] On the other hand, if the engine coolant gets too hot, it might boil while inside the engine, causing voids (pockets of steam), leading to localized hot spots and the catastrophic failure of the engine.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] If plain water were to be used as an engine coolant in northern climates freezing would occur, causing significant internal engine damage.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Also, plain water would increase the prevalence of galvanic corrosion.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Proper engine coolant and a pressurized coolant system obviate these shortcomings of water.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] With proper antifreeze, a wide temperature range can be tolerated by the engine coolant, such as −34 °F (−37 °C) to +265 °F (129 °C) for 50% (by volume) propylene glycol diluted with distilled water and a 15 psi pressurized coolant system.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Early engine coolant antifreeze was methanol (methyl alcohol).
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Ethylene glycol was developed because its higher boiling point was more compatible with heating systems.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] The Volkswagen Group has been particularly committed to the development of coolants and their standards (VW TL 774) in collaboration with Haertol Chemie from Magdeburg.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Another company involved in the development is BASF (Glysantin), whose standards are: G30, G40, G48, G05, G33, and G34.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] The most common water-based antifreeze solutions used in electronics cooling are mixtures of water and either ethylene glycol (EGW) or propylene glycol (PGW).
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] The use of ethylene glycol has a longer history, especially in the automotive industry.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] However, EGW solutions formulated for the automotive industry often have silicate based rust inhibitors that can coat and/or clog heat exchanger surfaces.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Ethylene glycol is listed as a toxic chemical requiring care in handling and disposal.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Ethylene glycol has desirable thermal properties, including a high boiling point, low freezing point, stability over a wide range of temperatures, and high specific heat and thermal conductivity.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] It also has a low viscosity and, therefore, reduced pumping requirements.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Although EGW has more desirable physical properties than PGW, the latter coolant is used in applications where toxicity might be a concern.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] PGW is generally recognized as safe for use in food or food processing applications, and can also be used in enclosed spaces.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Similar mixtures are commonly used in HVAC and industrial heating or cooling systems as a high-capacity heat transfer medium.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Many formulations have corrosion inhibitors, and it is expected that these chemicals will be replenished (manually or under automatic control) to keep expensive piping and equipment from corroding.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Antifreeze proteins refer to chemical compounds produced by certain animals, plants, and other organisms that prevent the formation of ice.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] In this way, these compounds allow their host organism to operate at temperatures well below the freezing point of water.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Antifreeze proteins bind to small ice crystals to inhibit growth and recrystallization of ice that would otherwise be fatal.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Cryoprotectants are commonly used in cryobiology to prevent or inhibit freezing in sperm, blood, stem cells, plant seeds, etc.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Ethylene glycol, propylene glycol, and glycerol (all used in automotive antifreeze) are commonly used as biological cryoprotectants.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Most antifreeze is made by mixing distilled water with additives and a base product, usually MEG (mono ethylene glycol) or MPG (mono propylene glycol).
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Ethylene glycol solutions first became available in 1926 and were marketed as "permanent antifreeze" since the higher boiling points provided advantages for summertime use as well as during cold weather.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] They are used today for a variety of applications, including automobiles, but there are lower-toxicity alternatives made with propylene glycol available.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] When ethylene glycol is used in a system, it may become oxidized to five organic acids (formic, oxalic, glycolic, glyoxalic and acetic acid).
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Inhibited ethylene glycol antifreeze mixes are available, with additives that buffer the pH and preserve alkalinity of the solution to prevent oxidation of ethylene glycol and formation of these acids.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Nitrites, silicates, borates and azoles may also be used to prevent corrosive attack on metal.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Ethylene glycol has a bitter, sweet taste and causes inebriation.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] The toxic effects of ingesting ethylene glycol occur because it is converted by the liver into 4 other chemicals that are much more toxic.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] The lethal dose of pure ethylene glycol is 1.4 ml/kg (3 US fluid ounces (90 ml) is lethal to a 140-pound (64 kg) person) but is much less lethal if treated within an hour.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Propylene glycol is considerably less toxic than ethylene glycol and may be labeled as "non-toxic antifreeze".
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] It is used as antifreeze where ethylene glycol would be inappropriate, such as in food-processing systems or in water pipes in homes where incidental ingestion may be possible.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] FDA allows propylene glycol to be added to a large number of ultra-processed foods, including ice cream, frozen custard, salad dressings, and baked goods, and it is commonly used as the main ingredient in the "e-liquid" used in electronic cigarettes.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Propylene glycol oxidizes to lactic acid.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Besides cooling system corrosion, biological fouling also occurs.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Once bacterial slime starts to grow, the corrosion rate of the system increases.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Maintenance of systems using glycol solution includes regular monitoring of freeze protection, pH, specific gravity, inhibitor level, color, and biological contamination.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Propylene glycol should be replaced when it turns a reddish color.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] When an aqueous solution of propylene glycol in a cooling or heating system develops a reddish or black color, this indicates that iron in the system is corroding significantly.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] In the absence of inhibitors, propylene glycol can react with oxygen and metal ions, generating various compounds including organic acids (e.g., formic, oxalic, acetic).
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] These acids accelerate the corrosion of metals in the system.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Propylene glycol methyl ether is used as an antifreeze in diesel engines.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Once used for automotive antifreeze, glycerol has the advantage of being non-toxic, withstands relatively high temperatures, and is noncorrosive.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Glycerol was historically used as an antifreeze for automotive applications before being replaced by ethylene glycol.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Volkswagen introduced *G13* (TL 774-G) antifreezes containing glycerol in 2008, marketed as better for the environment due to its low toxicity and reduced CO2 emissions.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] However, since 2018, they have moved on to *G12EVO* (TL 774-L) which no longer contains glycerol.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Glycerol is mandated for use as an antifreeze in many sprinkler systems.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Once antifreeze has been mixed with water and put into use, it periodically needs to be maintained.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] If engine coolant leaks, boils, or if the cooling system needs to be drained and refilled, the antifreeze's freeze protection will need to be considered.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] In other cases a vehicle may need to be operated in a colder environment, requiring more antifreeze and less water.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Test strips—specialized, disposable indicators made for this purpose.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Both specific gravity and refractive index are affected by temperature, although the former is affected much less catastrophically.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Temperature compensation is nevertheless recommended for RI measurement.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Propylene glycol solutions cannot be tested using specific gravity because of ambiguous results (40% and 100% solutions have the same specific gravity), although typical uses rarely exceed 60% concentration.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] The boiling point can be similarly determined by a concentration given from one of the three methods.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Datasheets for glycol/water coolant mixtures are commonly available from chemical vendors.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Most commercial antifreeze formulations include corrosion inhibiting compounds, and a colored dye (commonly a fluorescent green, red, orange, yellow, or blue) to aid in identification.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] A 1:1 dilution with water is usually used, resulting in a freezing point of about −34 °F (−37 °C), depending on the formulation.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] In warmer or colder areas, weaker or stronger dilutions are used, respectively, but a water/antifreeze ratio of 40/60 to 60/40 is frequently specified to ensure corrosion protection, and 70%/30% for maximum freeze prevention down to −84 °F (−64 °C).
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] In the absence of leaks, antifreeze chemicals such as ethylene glycol or propylene glycol may retain their basic properties indefinitely.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] By contrast, corrosion inhibitors are gradually used up, and must be replenished from time to time.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Larger systems (such as HVAC systems) are often monitored by specialist firms which take responsibility for adding corrosion inhibitors and regulating coolant composition.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] For simplicity, most automotive manufacturers recommend periodic complete replacement of engine coolant, to simultaneously renew corrosion inhibitors and remove accumulated contaminants.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Traditionally, there were two major corrosion inhibitors used in vehicles: silicates and phosphates.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] American-made vehicles traditionally used both silicates and phosphates.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] European makes contain silicates and other inhibitors, but no phosphates.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Japanese makes traditionally use phosphates and other inhibitors, but no silicates.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Most modern cars are built with organic acid technology (OAT) antifreeze (e.g., DEX-COOL), or with a hybrid organic acid technology (HOAT) formulation (e.g., Zerex G-05), both of which are claimed to have an extended service life of five years or 240,000 km (150,000 mi).
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] DEX-COOL specifically has caused controversy.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Litigation has linked it with intake manifold gasket failures in General Motors' (GM's) 3.1L and 3.4L engines, and with other failures in 3.8L and 4.3L engines.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] One of the anti-corrosion components presented as sodium or potassium 2-ethylhexanoate and ethylhexanoic acid is incompatible with nylon 6,6 and silicone rubber, and is a known plasticizer.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Class action lawsuits were registered in several states of the US, and in Canada, to address some of these claims.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] The first of these to reach a decision was in Missouri, where a settlement was announced early in December 2007.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Late in March 2008, GM agreed to compensate complainants in the remaining 49 states.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] GM (Motors Liquidation Company) filed for bankruptcy in 2009, which tied up the outstanding claims until a court determines who gets paid.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] According to the DEX-COOL manufacturer, "mixing a 'green' [non-OAT] coolant with DEX-COOL reduces the batch's change interval to 2 years or 50,000 km (30,000 mi), but will otherwise cause no damage to the engine".
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] DEX-COOL antifreeze uses two inhibitors: sebacate and 2-EHA (2-ethylhexanoic acid), the latter which works well with the hard water found in the United States, but is a plasticizer that can cause gaskets to leak.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] According to internal GM documents, the ultimate culprit appears to be operating vehicles for long periods of time with low coolant levels.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] The low coolant is caused by pressure caps that fail in the open position.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] (The new caps and recovery bottles were introduced at the same time as DEX-COOL).
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] This exposes hot engine components to air and vapors, causing corrosion and contamination of the coolant with iron oxide particles, which in turn can aggravate the pressure cap problem as contamination holds the caps open permanently.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Honda and Toyota's new extended life coolants use OAT with sebacate, but without the 2-EHA.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Some added phosphates provide protection while the OAT builds up.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Honda specifically excludes 2-EHA from its formulas.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Typically, OAT antifreeze contains an orange dye to differentiate it from the conventional glycol-based coolants (green or yellow), though some OAT products may contain a red or mauve dye.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Some of the newer OAT coolants claim to be compatible with *all* types of OAT and glycol-based coolants; these are typically green or yellow in color.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] HOAT coolants typically mix an OAT with a traditional inhibitor, usually silicates.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] An example is Zerex G05, which is a low-silicate, phosphate free formula that includes the benzoate inhibitor.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] A HOAT coolant can have a life expectancy as high as 10 years / 180,000 miles.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] P-HOAT coolants mix phosphates with HOAT.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] This technology is typically used in Asian makes and is often dyed red or blue.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Si-OAT coolants mix silicates with HOAT.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] This technology is typically used in European makes and is often dyed pink.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] All automotive antifreeze formulations, including the newer organic acid (OAT antifreeze) formulations, are environmentally hazardous because of the blend of additives (around 5%), including lubricants, buffers, and corrosion inhibitors.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Because the additives in antifreeze are proprietary, the safety data sheets (SDS) provided by the manufacturer list only those compounds which are considered to be significant safety hazards when used in accordance with the manufacturer's recommendations.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Common additives include sodium silicate, disodium phosphate, sodium molybdate, sodium borate, denatonium benzoate, and dextrin (hydroxyethyl starch).
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Disodium fluorescein dye is added to conventional ethylene glycol formulas to visually distinguish leaked amounts from other vehicle fluids, and as a marker of type to distinguish it from incompatible types.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] This dye fluoresces bright green when illuminated by blue or UV light from daylight or testing lamps.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Automotive antifreeze has a characteristic odor due to the additive tolyltriazole, a corrosion inhibitor.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] The unpleasant odor in industrial-use tolyltriazole comes from impurities in the product that are formed from the toluidine isomers (ortho-, meta-, and para-toluidine) and meta-diamino toluene which are side-products in the manufacture of tolyltriazole.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] These side-products are highly reactive and produce volatile aromatic amines which are responsible for the unpleasant odor.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Ethylene glycol, the main ingredient in some antifreeze, is poisonous to both people and other mammals.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] After ethylene glycol is ingested, it is metabolized in the liver into various intermediate substances, which then get turned into oxalic acid.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Oxalic acid is incredibly dangerous as it can cause, among other ailments, kidney failure, which is why a major treatment for antifreeze poisoning is kidney dialysis.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Common symptoms of poisoning are vomiting, confusion, abdominal pain, agitation, ataxia and hematuria.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Long term damage such as kidney damage, brain damage, central nervous system damage, and blindness are common.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Antifreeze may be consumed by children and pets for its sweet taste, and is also commonly consumed as a surrogate alcohol due to its high alcohol content.
[src:core-plug/antifreeze] Many formulations include bitter additives to discourage consumption due to taste; however, many studies do not support embittering antifreeze to reduce its ingestion.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] An **automotive battery**, or **car battery**, is a rechargeable battery that is used to start a motor vehicle, and to power lights, screen wiper etc. while the engine is off.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Its main purpose is to provide an electric current to the electric-powered starting motor, which in turn starts the chemically-powered internal combustion engine that actually propels the vehicle.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Once the engine is running, power for the car's electrical systems is still supplied by the battery, with the alternator charging the battery as demands increase or decrease.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Typically, starting uses less than three percent of the battery capacity.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] For this reason, automotive batteries are designed to deliver maximum current for a short period of time.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] They are sometimes referred to as "SLI batteries" for this reason, for starting, lighting and ignition.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] SLI batteries are not designed for deep discharging, and a full discharge can reduce the battery's lifespan.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] As well as starting the engine, an SLI battery supplies the extra power necessary when the vehicle's electrical requirements exceed the supply from the charging system.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] It is also a stabilizer, evening out potentially damaging voltage spikes.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] While the engine is running most of the power is provided by the alternator (or in older vehicles a generator or dynamo), which includes a voltage regulator to keep the output between 13.5 and 14.5 V.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Modern SLI batteries are lead-acid type, using six series-connected cells to provide a nominal 12-volt system (in most passenger vehicles and light trucks), or twelve cells for a 24-volt system in heavy trucks or earth-moving equipment, for example.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Gas explosions can occur at the negative electrode where hydrogen gas can build up due to blocked battery vents or a poorly ventilated setting, combined with an ignition source.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Explosions during engine start-up are typically associated with corroded or dirty battery posts.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] A 1993 study by the US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said that 31% of vehicle battery explosion injuries occurred while charging the battery.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Close to two-thirds of those injured suffered chemical burns, and nearly three-fourths suffered eye injuries, among other possible injuries.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Electric vehicles (EVs) are powered by a high-voltage electric vehicle battery, but they usually have an automotive battery as well, so that they can use standard automotive accessories which are designed to run on 12 V.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Unlike conventional, internal combustion engined vehicles, EVs don't charge the auxiliary battery with an alternator—instead, they use a DC-to-DC converter to step down the high voltage to the required float-charge voltage (typically around 14 V).
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Further, an electric vehicle does not have a starter motor, thus needs only a limited amount of power and energy from its auxiliary battery.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] As such, Tesla introduced in 2021 a lithium-ion auxiliary battery storing only 99 Wh of energy.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Early cars did not have batteries, as their electrical systems were limited.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Electric power for the ignition was provided by a magneto, the engine was started with a crank, headlights were gas-powered and a bell or bulb-horn was used instead of an electric horn.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Car batteries became widely used around 1920 as cars became equipped with electric starter motors.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] The first starting and charging systems were designed to be 6-volt and positive-ground systems, with the vehicle's chassis directly connected to the positive battery terminal.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Today, almost all road vehicles have a negative ground system.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] The negative battery terminal is connected to the car's chassis.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] The Hudson Motor Car Company was the first to use a standardized battery in 1918 when they started using Battery Council International batteries.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] BCI is the organization that sets the dimensional standards for batteries.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Cars used 6 V electrical systems and batteries until the mid-1950s.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] The changeover from 6 to 12 V happened when bigger engines with higher compression ratios required more electrical power to start.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Smaller cars, which required less power to start stayed with 6 V longer, for example the Volkswagen Beetle in the mid-1960s and the Citroën 2CV in 1970.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] The AGM sealed battery (for automobiles), which did not require refilling, was invented in 1971.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] In the 1990s a 42V electrical system standard was proposed.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] It was intended to allow more powerful electrically driven accessories, and lighter automobile wiring harnesses.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] However, the availability of higher-efficiency motors, new wiring techniques, and digital controls, and a focus on hybrid vehicle systems that use high-voltage starter/generators have largely eliminated the push for switching the main automotive voltages.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] In 2023 Tesla started deliveries of their Cybertruck that uses a 48-volt electrical system, reducing 70% of the wiring in the vehicle.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] An automobile battery is an example of a wet cell battery, with six cells.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Each cell of a lead storage battery consists of alternate plates made of a lead alloy grid filled with sponge lead plates (cathode) or coated with lead dioxide (anode).
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Each cell is filled with a sulfuric acid solution, which is the electrolyte.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Initially, cells each had a filler cap, through which the electrolyte level could be viewed and which allowed water to be added to the cell.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] The filler cap had a small vent hole which allowed hydrogen gas generated during charging to escape from the cell.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] The cells are connected by short heavy straps from the positive plates of one cell to the negative plates of the adjacent cell.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] A pair of heavy terminals, plated with lead to resist corrosion, are mounted at the top, sometimes the side, of the battery.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Early auto batteries used hard rubber cases and wooden plate separators.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Modern units use plastic cases and woven sheets to prevent the plates of a cell from touching and short-circuiting.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] In the past, auto batteries required regular inspection and maintenance to replace water that was decomposed during the operation of the battery.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] "Low-maintenance" (sometimes called "zero-maintenance") batteries use a different alloy for the plate elements, reducing the amount of water decomposed on charging.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] A modern battery may not require additional water over its useful life; some types eliminate the individual filler caps for each cell.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] A weakness of these batteries is that they are very intolerant of deep discharge, such as when the car battery is completely drained by leaving the lights on.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] This coats the lead plate electrodes with lead sulfate deposits and can reduce the battery's lifespan by a third or more.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries, also known as absorbed glass mat (AGM) batteries are more tolerant of deep discharge but are more expensive.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries do not permit addition of water to the cell.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] The cells each have an automatic pressure release valve, to protect the case from rupture on severe overcharge or internal failure.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] A VRLA battery cannot spill its electrolyte which makes it particularly useful in vehicles such as motorcycles.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Batteries are typically made of six galvanic cells in a series circuits.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Each cell provides 2.1 volts for a total of 12.6 volts at full charge.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] During discharge, at the negative (lead) terminal a chemical reaction releases electrons to the external circuit, and at the positive (lead oxide) terminal another chemical reaction absorbs electrons from the external circuit.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] This drives the electrons through the external circuit wire (an electrical conductor) to produce an electric current (electricity).
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] As the battery discharges, the acid of the electrolyte reacts with the materials of the plates, changing their surface to lead sulfate.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] When the battery is recharged, the chemical reaction is reversed: the lead sulfate reforms into lead dioxide.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] With the plates restored to their original condition, the process may be repeated.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Some vehicles use other starter batteries.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] For weight savings, the 2010 Porsche 911 GT3 RS has a lithium-ion battery as an option; from 2018 onward, all Kia Niro conventional hybrids feature one as well.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Heavy vehicles may have two batteries in series for a 24 V system or may have series-parallel groups of batteries supplying 24 V.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Batteries are grouped by physical size, type and placement of the terminals, and mounting style.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Battery Council International (BCI) group size specifies a battery's physical dimensions, such as length, width, and height.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] These groups are determined by the organization.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Ampere hours (Ah or A·h) is a unit related to the energy storage capacity of the battery.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] This rating is required by law in Europe.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] The ampere hour rating represents the total current delivered over a period of 20 hours before voltage drops below 10.5 volts while operating at a temperature of 80 °F (26.6 °C).
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] In theory, at 80 °F, a 100 Ah battery should be able to continuously provide 5 amps for 20 hours while maintaining a voltage of at least 10.5 volts.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] The relationship between the Ah capacity and the discharge rate is not linear; as the discharge rate is increased, the capacity decreases.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] A battery with a 100 Ah rating generally will not be able to maintain a voltage above 10.5 volts for 10 hours while being discharged at constant rate of 10 amps.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Capacity also decreases with temperature.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Excess heat is a main cause of battery failures, as when the electrolyte evaporates due to high temperatures, decreasing the effective surface area of the plates exposed to the electrolyte, and leading to sulfation.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Grid corrosion rates increase with temperature.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Also low temperatures can lead to battery failure.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] If the battery is discharged to the point where it can't start the engine, the engine can be jump started via an external source of power.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Once running, the engine can recharge the battery, if the alternator and charging system are undamaged.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Corrosion at the battery terminals can prevent a car from starting due to electrical resistance, which can be prevented by the proper application of dielectric grease.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Sulfation is when the electrodes become coated with a hard layer of lead sulfate, which weakens the battery.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Sulfation can happen when battery is not fully charged and remains discharged.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Sulfated batteries should be charged slowly to prevent damage.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] SLI batteries (starting, lighting, and ignition) are not designed for deep discharge, and their life is reduced when subjected to this.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Starting batteries have plates designed for increased surface area and thus high instant current capability, whereas marine (hybrid) and deep cycle types will have thicker plates and more room at the bottom of the plates for spent plate material to gather before shorting the cell.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Car batteries using lead-antimony plates require regular topping-up with pure water to replace water lost due to electrolysis and evaporation.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] By changing the alloying element to calcium, more recent designs have reduced the rate of water loss.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Modern car batteries have reduced maintenance requirements, and may not provide caps for addition of water to the cells.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Such batteries include extra electrolyte above the plates to allow for losses during the battery life.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Some battery manufacturers include a built-in hydrometer to show the state of charge of the battery.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] The primary wear-out mechanism is the shedding of active material from the battery plates, which accumulates at the bottom of the cells and which may eventually short-circuit the plates.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] This can be substantially reduced by enclosing one set of plates in plastic separator bags, made from a permeable material.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] This allows the electrolyte and ions to pass through but keeps the sludge build up from bridging the plates.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] The sludge largely consists of lead sulfate, which is produced at both electrodes.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Battery recycling of automotive batteries reduces the need for resources required for the manufacture of new batteries, diverts toxic lead from landfills, and prevents the risk of improper disposal.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Once a lead–acid battery ceases to hold a charge, it is deemed a used lead-acid battery (ULAB), which is classified as hazardous waste under the Basel Convention.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] The 12-volt car battery is the most recycled product in the world, according to the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] In the U.S. alone, about 130 million auto batteries a year are replaced, and 99 percent of them are turned in for recycling.[1] However, the recycling may be done incorrectly in unregulated environments.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] As part of global waste trade, ULABs are shipped from industrialized countries to developing countries for disassembly and recuperation of the contents.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] About 97 percent of the lead can be recovered.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Pure Earth estimates that over 12 million people in developing countries are affected by lead contamination from ULAB processing.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] ULAB recycling has been used as an example supporting the pollution haven hypothesis.
[src:core-plug/automotive-battery] Following this change, American exports of used lead-acid batteries to Mexico increased four-fold, which was followed by a significant increase in babies born with low birth weight to mothers living within a two-mile (3.2 km) radius of Mexican battery-recycling plants.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] Sand cores are used to form the internal cavities when the engine block or cylinder head(s) are cast.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] These cavities are usually the coolant passages.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] Holes are designed into the casting to support internal sand forms and to facilitate the removal of the sand after the casting has cooled.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] These holes generally have no factory designed purpose after the sand has been removed although some aftermarket temperature sensors may be installed into the location of a core plug on some engine designs.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] Another use is to install an aftermarket system designed to act as a block heater which is installed to keep an engine warm due to sub-freezing temperatures as found in far northern climates such as in Scandinavia, Canada, northern Russia, or the state of Alaska.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] One of the purposes of core plugs is to serve as a cap at the end of these passages used to prevent water or a coolant mixture from leaking out of the engine.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] Core plugs can also sometimes prevent freeze damage to the motor.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] During the early stages of the freezing of the engine coolant a freeze plug will sometimes burst or pop out, and thus allow the coolant to exit the engine, before it might expand within the engine during the freezing process and potentially crack the engine block.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] Core plugs are usually thin metal cups press fitted into the casting holes, but may be made of rubber or other materials.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] The most common metal plugs used in automotive engines are made from plated mild steels, stainless steels, brass or bronze.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] In some high-performance engines the core plugs are large diameter cast metal threaded pipe plugs.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] Core plugs can often be a source of leaks due to corrosion caused by cooling system water.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] Although modern antifreeze chemicals do not evaporate and may be considered "permanent", anti-corrosion additives gradually deplete and must be replenished via a flush and refill.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] Automotive manufacturers specify time and mileage numbers for cooling system maintenance in their published factory maintenance manuals.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] The slang term "freeze plug" was coined many decades ago based on the mistaken belief that the primary purpose of the core plugs was to protect the engine block against freezing.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] Core plugs were initially designed merely as a necessary engine block component which was made necessary due to the "sand casting" method used to initially form an engine block.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] After the initial casting of the engine block, core plugs were designed to plug off the "sand exit ports" of the newly formed engine block.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] Only many years after they were first introduced was it found that they sometimes acted to reduce the possibility of the cracking of the engine block during a freeze.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] The Welch plug is a type of core plug that is made from a thin disc of metal.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] The Welch plug is dome-shaped and inserted into the casting hole with the convex side facing outwards.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] When installed by striking the Welch plug with a hammer, the dome collapses slightly, expanding it laterally to seal the hole.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] This differs from other dish-shaped core plug designs, which form a seal when their tapered sides are pressed into the casting hole.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] The Welch plug was originally designed in the 1900s at the Welch Motor Car Company in the United States.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] Prior to the invention of the Welch plug, the core holes were sealed using pipe plugs.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] During the testing of a car, one of the pipe plugs backed out.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] In order to get back on the road, one of the Welch brothers installed a press-fit quarter or half dollar coin into the hole using a hammer.
[src:core-plug/core-plug] The design of the Welch plug was refined based on this principle of a press-fit metallic disc.
